<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="47" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[204,1695,988,1598]" pageId="4" pageNumber="47">
This distinctive species was originally described from Malawi. The male terminalia (
<figureCitation box="[218,321,1148,1186]" captionStart="Figs 1-5" captionStartId="2.[210,272,2476,2508]" captionTargetBox="[255,1619,337,2380]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1-5. Choerades species; dorsal aspect of cr genital bulb 1. C. aureopilosa (Ricardo). 2. C. bella (Loew). 3. C. jlavipes (Weidemann). 4. C. nigrescens (Ricardo) 5. C. serpentina (Bezzi)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1472447/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="47">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
) have not been adequately described before.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[204,1695,988,1598]" pageId="4" pageNumber="47">
Fused gonopodal setae (4 in each group) short, straight and inwardly directed. Inner setae shorter than outer setae giving the fused group a characteristic shape (
<figureCitation box="[217,328,1298,1336]" captionStart="Figs 1-5" captionStartId="2.[210,272,2476,2508]" captionTargetBox="[255,1619,337,2380]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1-5. Choerades species; dorsal aspect of cr genital bulb 1. C. aureopilosa (Ricardo). 2. C. bella (Loew). 3. C. jlavipes (Weidemann). 4. C. nigrescens (Ricardo) 5. C. serpentina (Bezzi)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1472447/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="47">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). Distal processes of gonopods blunt and inwardly directed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
